data.title: WF Holding receives Nasdaq notice for minimum bid price deficiency
data.description:
• WF Holding Limited (WFF) on Thursday said it has received a notice from the Nasdaq Stock Market stating that the company is not in compliance with the exchange’s $1.00 minimum bid price requirement after its shares closed below that level for 30 consecutive business days.

  • The notification, dated October 28, 2025, has no immediate effect on the listing of WF Holding’s shares, which will continue to trade on Nasdaq under the ticker “WFF.”

  • The Malaysia-based fiberglass reinforced plastic products maker has 180 calendar days, until April 27, 2026, to regain compliance by maintaining a closing bid price of at least $1.00 per share for ten consecutive business days.

  • WFF closed -5.38% at $0.7664.
  • Source: Press Release

data.title: GENFIT to delist American depositary shares from Nasdaq
data.description:
• French biopharmaceutical company GENFIT S.A. (Nasdaq, Euronext: GNFT) said on Thursday it will voluntarily delist its American Depositary Shares (ADSs) from the Nasdaq Global Select Market to simplify its corporate structure and improve operational efficiency.

  • The delisting is expected to take effect before U.S. markets open on Nov. 20, 2025, after which the ADSs will no longer trade on Nasdaq.

  • GENFIT’s ordinary shares will continue to trade on Euronext Paris, its primary listing.

  • GENFIT said it will file a Form 25 with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission to initiate the delisting, followed by a Form 15F to deregister its securities and suspend SEC reporting obligations.

  • GNFTF closed +13.41% at $3.72.
  • Source: Press Release

data.title: FMC sinks to 15-year lows after cutting dividend, full-year guidance; Barclays downgrades
data.description:
FMC (FMC) -46.7% in Thursday's trading to its lowest since 2009 after reporting a nearly 50% Y/Y decline in Q3 revenues to just $542 million compared to analyst expectations of ~$1 billion, mostly the result of one-time actions in India as the company prepares to sell its India business.

Excluding India, Q3 revenues totaled $961 million, 10% lower than the previous year, which included India, and down 11% organically, driven by lower pricing.

FMC (FMC) also cut FY 2025 revenue guidance to $3.9 billion-$4 billion and now expects negative free cash flow up to $200 million; for Q4, the company sees adjusted EPS of $1.14-$1.36 or revenues of $1.12 billion-$1.22 billion, below $1.75 and $1.3 billion FactSet consensus, respectively.

The company cut its quarterly dividend to $0.08/share from $0.58 to prioritize debt reduction.

Barclays downgraded FMC (FMC) shares to Equal Weight from Overweight with a $22 price target, slashed from $48, seeing little reason to remain constructive "given soft results, limited to no visibility on earnings in coming quarters, and a surprise cut of its dividend."

Given the dividend cut, Barclays analyst Benjamin Theurer said improvement in 2026 seems unlikely, paired with the overhang in expiring patents which will adversely impact company financials, which ruins confidence in original estimates for 2026.
